{{Earth_Impact_Database_world_map.svg|480px}} The '''Earth Impact Database''' is a database of confirmed [[impact structure]]s or [[impact crater|crater]]s on [[Earth]]. It was initiated in 1955 by the [[Dominion Observatory]], Ottawa, under the direction of Dr. [[Carlyle Smith Beals|Carlyle S. Beals]]. Since 2001, it has been maintained as a not-for-profit source of information at the Planetary and Space Science Centre at the [[University of New Brunswick]], Canada.<ref name="EID">{{cite web | title = Earth Impact Database | publisher = [[University of New Brunswick]] | url = http://www.passc.net/EarthImpactDatabase/index.html | accessdate = 3 August 2016 }}</ref>
{{As of|2016|08}}, the database lists 190 confirmed impact sites.<ref name="EID" />
Other lists are wider in scope by including more than just confirmed sites, such as probable, possible, suspected and rejected or discredited impact sites on their lists. These are used for screening and tracking study of possible impact sites. The reason to retain rejected sites on such a list is because they may be, and often are, reported again. Sites will appear first in these lists while under study and may be incorporated into UNB's Earth Impact Database after confirmation and collection of enough information about the site to satisfy the database's strict entry criteria.<ref>{{cite web | first = D. | last = Rajmon | title = Suspected Earth Impact Sites | publisher = [[Lunar and Planetary Institute]] | date = March 13–17, 2006 | url = http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/lpsc2006/pdf/2372.pdf | accessdate = 2008-09-24 }}</ref> * Impact Database (formerly Suspected Earth Impact Sites (SEIS)), [[Impact Field Studies Group]] (IFSG)<ref>{{cite web | last = Rajmon | first = David | title = Impact Database | publisher = [Impact Field Studies Group (IFSG)] | date = 2009-07-01 | url = http://impacts.rajmon.cz/ | accessdate = 2009-08-12 }} </ref> * Catalogue of the Earth's Impact structures, Siberian Center for Global Catastrophes<ref>{{cite web |title = Catalogue of the Earth's Impact structures |publisher = Siberian Center for Global Catastrophes, [[Russian Academy of Sciences]], Siberian division |date = |url = http://omzg.sscc.ru/impact/index1.html |accessdate = 2009-08-12 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090716232605/http://omzg.sscc.ru/impact/index1.html |archivedate = 2009-07-16 |df = }}</ref>
